Through his Twitter account, the club’s tough-talking owner, Swedish tycoon Ricardo Badoer came under fire for referring to the players as “hyenas” due to bad performance. 

He claimed that the sacking of the players was a cleaning process, since “most of them were signed behind his back”. 

“K’Ogalo” were not left behind. British tactician Steven Polack, 59, left the club under unclear circumstances after being at the helm for 13 months. 






Gor Mahia coach Steven Polack gestures during their friendly match against Ksports on March 11, 2020 Parklands Sports Club.
Photo credit: Chris Omollo | Nation Media Group

 

He resigned in September while on a 10-day holiday in the United Kingdom. 

The Briton joined a growing list of Gor coaches who “go on holidays” in their homeland but never to return. Polack became the fourth Gor coach to leave the club in such manner. 

Before him, were Dylan Kerr, Turkish-Cypriot Hassan Oktay, and Brazilian Jose Marcelo Ferreira aka Ze Maria. 

Polack had a colourful stay at Gor, he won the Sports Journalist Association of Kenya (SJAK) Coach for the Month of September/October in 2019 and in February 2020. 

This month, another Gor Mahia coach Brazilian Roberto Oliveira, Polack’s successor, quit.  

The 60-year-old Brazilian tactician, 60, never oversaw any competitive match for Gor because he lacked the requisite coaching credentials. 



