The African football governing body, Caf, wrote to FKF and Gor on November 21, notifying them that the former Brazilian international player didn’t have a Caf “A” coaching licence or Uefa Pro, its equivalent, and therefore he was not eligible to oversee “K’Ogalo’s” continental assignment. 

'Unsafe in the country' 

AFC Leopards were not short of drama either. Their new coach, Tomas Trucha, resigned just a month into his job citing threats to his agent. The Czech said he felt unsafe in the country. 






AFC Leopards coach Tomas Trucha gestures from the touchline during their FKF Premier League match against Tusker FC on November 28, 2020 at Kasarani.
Photo credit: Chris Omollo | Nation Media Group

 

Trucha, who previously handled Botswana’s Township Rollers, was in charge of just one game for Ingwe which bagged a 2-1 win against Tusker Football Club in the opening week of 2020/21 Premier League campaign. 

The 40-year-old has since landed a new job in Malaysia. Leopards are now being managed by their former player and Kenyan international Anthony “Modo” Kimani, assisted by Tom Juma. 

Last season, Bandari were the first to axe their coach, Bernard Mwalala, just 13 days into the New Year after a string of poor results in the league. 

After Mwalala’s dismissal, the club turned to former Harambee Stars coach Twahir Muhiddin to hold the position in an acting capacity. Bandari management reappointed Ken Odhiambo who had left the club in 2018 for further studies in South Sudan. 



