During his two-year stint at Bandari,  Mwalala won the Betway Shield, catapulting the Dockers to the continental competitions after four years in the cold. Bandari also finished second twice and won silver in the Super Cup. 

In November last year, Bandari were eliminated from the Caf Confederation Cup at the play-offs stage by Horoya FC of Guinea in a two-legged contest. They fell 1-0 to the Guinea heavyweights at the Moi International Sports Centre, Kasarani after being beaten 4-2 away in the first leg. 

The 2009 league champions Sofapaka sacked coach John Baraza early this month. 

Sofapaka President Elly Kelekwa denied that he was sacked, saying that the former Kenyan international was asked to step aside. 






 "We have asked coach Baraza to step aside as we plan to take him for further studies either in Norway or Germany. For now, Mururi (Mike) is in charge of the team as we prepare for our next match," said Kalekwa. 

Baraza was appointed in December last year after serving as a stand-in coach thrice but his decade-long stay at the club both as a player and a member of the technical bench ended after two losses suffered in the opening three matches of the new season. 

After his departure, Kalekwa said his assistant and former Kenyan international, Mururi, will take over in an acting capacity. 



